In this paper we present three examples where we describe the ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{VPS}}}_X(f,r_f)$ 
where $X$ is a toric surface different from the projective plane, $f$ a general section in~$S_A$ for some $A\in {\ensuremath{\mathrm{Pic}}}(X)$ and $r_f$  the minimal integer~$r$ such that ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{VPS}}}_X(f,r)$  is not empty.
The paper is structured in the following way. 
In Section~\ref{prelim} we set up the theory for apolarity in the case $X= 
{\ensuremath{{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1\times{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1}}$. We prove the following two theorems in Sections~\ref{biquadratic} and~\ref{bicubic}, respectively.   

\begin{theorem}\label{A}
Let $X={\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1\times {\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1$, $A=(2,2)\in {\ensuremath{\mathrm{Pic}}}(X)$ and $f\in S_A$ be a general section.
The ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{VPS}}}_{\ensuremath{{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1\times{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1}}(f,4)$ is a threefold isomorphic to a smooth linear complex in 
the Grassmannian $G(2,4)$ blown up along a smooth rational normal quartic curve.
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem} \label{B}
Let $X={\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1\times {\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1$, $A=(3,3)\in {\ensuremath{\mathrm{Pic}}}(X)$ and $f\in S_A$ be a general section.
The ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{VPS}}}_{\ensuremath{{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1\times{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^1}}(f,6)$ is isomorphic to a smooth Del Pezzo surface of degree $5$.
\end{theorem}

In Section~\ref{cubicone} we focus on the case $X = F_1$, namely the blow up of ${\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^2$ in one point embedded as a cubic scroll in ${\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^4$. We prove the following result. 

\begin{theorem} \label{C}
Let $X=F_1$ with hyperplane class $H$, let $A=3H$ and $f\in S_A$ be a general section.
The ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{VPS}}}_{F_1}(f,8)$ is isomorphic to ${\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}}}^2$ blown up in $8$ points.
\end{theorem}

